Introduction:¶

In this study we will try to predict the next french lottery numbers. 91 draws were realized since february 2019. We will take advantage of the LSTM architecture to achieve this goal.

Time series analysis¶

Lets investigate the series of each drawing orders:

In [200]:
dic = {i:[Tirages[j][i] for j in range(len(Tirages))] for i in range(6)}
In [201]:
plots = ["23{}".format(i) for i in range(1,7)]
In [202]:
f = plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
for i in range(len(dic)):
    ax = f.add_subplot(plots[i])
    ax.plot(dic[i],label="Boule n{}".format(i+1))
    median = round(np.median(dic[i]))
    mean = round(np.mean(dic[i]))
    std = round(np.std(dic[i]))
    ax.legend()
      
    ax.set_title("Median: {0}, Mean: {1}, Std: {2}".format(median,mean,std))
f.suptitle("Raw series",fontsize=20)
plt.show()

Each series appears to be well balanced.

In [203]:
def autocorr(x, t=1):
    return np.corrcoef(np.array([x[:-t], x[t:]]))

f = plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
for i in range(len(dic)):
    ac = [(np.min(autocorr(dic[i],lag)[0]),lag) for lag in range(1,100)]
    ax = f.add_subplot(plots[i])
    ax.plot([lag[1] for lag in ac],[lag[0] for lag in ac],label="Boule n{}".format(i+1))
    interesting = [lag[0] for lag in ac if lag[1]<50]
    best_lag = interesting.index(np.max(interesting))+1
    plt.vlines(x=best_lag, ymin=-0.3, ymax = 0.5,linestyle='dashed',color="orange")
    ax.legend()
    
    ax.set_title("Best lag: t={}".format(best_lag))
f.suptitle("Raw series autocorrelations",fontsize=20)
plt.show()

For each series, we look for the best partial autocorrelation (lag t < 50%). The results suggest the existance of repeated patterns for "boule 2" and "boule 3". It's intersting to know that since redondant information are "good features" for an LSTM model.

Robust lags are resistant to log transformation. Let's apply it:

In [204]:
f = plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
for i in range(len(dic)):
    ac = [(np.min(autocorr(np.log(dic[i]),lag)[0]),lag) for lag in range(1,100)]
    ax = f.add_subplot(plots[i])
    ax.plot([lag[1] for lag in ac],[lag[0] for lag in ac],label="Boule n{}".format(i+1))
    interesting = [lag[0] for lag in ac if lag[1]<50]
    best_lag = interesting.index(np.max(interesting))+1
    plt.vlines(x=best_lag, ymin=-0.3, ymax = 0.5,linestyle='dashed',color="orange")
    ax.legend()
    ax.set_title("Best lag: t={}".format(best_lag))
f.suptitle("log10 series autocorrelations",fontsize=20)
plt.show()

The "boule 2" best lag has increased indicating that the time serie is less autocorrelated.

We can consider another approach for the data by taking the drawset as a single flat time serie.

In [213]:
flat = np.array(Tirages).flatten()
f = plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
ax = f.add_subplot(121)
ax.plot(flat,label="Flat serie")
ax.set_xlabel("Ball drawing timeline")
ax.set_ylabel("Number")
ax.legend()
ax1 = f.add_subplot(122)
ac = [(np.min(autocorr(flat,lag)[0]),lag) for lag in range(1,len(flat))]
ax1.plot([lag[1] for lag in ac],[lag[0] for lag in ac],label="Flat serie")
interesting = [lag[0] for lag in ac if lag[1]<50]
best_lag = interesting.index(np.max(interesting))+1
plt.vlines(x=best_lag, ymin=-0.3, ymax = 0.5,linestyle='dashed',color="orange")
ax1.legend()
ax1.set_xlabel("lag")
ax1.set_ylabel("Correlation coefficient")
ax1.set_title("Best lag: t={}".format(best_lag))
plt.show()

Above results indicates a stable partial autocorrelation of the time series (correlation coefficient = 25 %). We choose the use this data to instanciate the LSTM model.

Time serie processing¶

Here, we will apply a simple moving average:

In [217]:
def moving_average(list,size):
    return [np.mean(list[i:i+size]) for i in range(len(list)-size)]
    
stds_wins = [(np.std(moving_average(flat,size)),size) 
             for size in range(30)]

plt.plot([i[1] for i in stds_wins],[i[0] for i in stds_wins],
         label="Standard deviation")
#plt.hlines(y=850,xmin=3,xmax=7,linestyle="--")
#plt.vlines(x=5,ymin=700,ymax=1000,linestyle="--")
plt.xlabel('Window size')
plt.ylabel("Standard deviation of windows means")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

We look for the elbow to select the window size. Here, 8 appears to be a good choice.

In [220]:
flat_av = moving_average(flat,8)
plt.plot(flat_av,label="Averaging, ws=8")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

The data appears to be really stationary. That's good for the model since there are no outliers. However, the data is also uniformly distributed and it may prevent the model to learn robust features.

To take account of this, we will trend up the data by multipling the values by their ranks.

In [222]:
flat_av_tr = [flat_av[i]*i for i in range(len(flat_av))]
plt.plot(flat_av_tr,label="Trended")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Model initialization¶

The data are trended and look great, let's build the model:

In [272]:
X = [[i] for i in flat_av_tr]
In [273]:
split = int(0.90*len(X))
In [274]:
X_train = X[0:split]
X_test = X[split:]
In [275]:
## Scale the data 
scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range = (0, 1))
scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
scaled_test = scaler.fit_transform(X_test)
In [276]:
## We define a window size (conventionnal ratio is 5%)
ws = round(0.05*len(X_train))
In [277]:
## Then convert the training to the right format
features_set = np.array([scaled[i-ws:i,0] for i in range(ws,len(X_train))])
labels = np.array([scaled[i,0] for i in range(ws,len(X_train))])
features_set = np.reshape(features_set, (features_set.shape[0], features_set.shape[1], 1))
In [278]:
test_features = np.array([scaled_test[i-ws:i,0] for i in range(ws,len(X_test))])
test_features = np.reshape(test_features, (test_features.shape[0], test_features.shape[1], 1))
In [279]:
model = Sequential()

model.add(LSTM(units=30,return_sequences=True, input_shape=(features_set.shape[1], 1)))
model.add(Dropout(0.1))
model.add(LSTM(units=10))
model.add(Dense(units = 1))

model.compile(optimizer='adam',  # Optimizer
              # Loss function to minimize
              loss="mean_absolute_error",
              # List of metrics to monitor
              metrics=["mean_squared_error"])
In [280]:
history = model.fit(features_set, labels, epochs =150, batch_size = 100)

    X_test.append(predictions[-1])
    scaled_test = scaler.fit_transform(X_test)
    test_features = np.array([scaled_test[i-ws:i,0] for i in range(ws,len(X_test))])
    test_features = np.reshape(test_features, (test_features.shape[0], test_features.shape[1], 1))
    # Make predictions
    predictions = model.predict(test_features)
    # Unscale the predictions
    predictions = scaler.inverse_transform(predictions)
